<div id="review_39813874" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/39813874" />
    <a title="Patrick Gibson" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1758594-patrick-gibson"><img alt="Patrick Gibson" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1228068580p2/1758594.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/39813874?book_show_action=true">Dec 10, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Patrick Gibson" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Patrick Gibson" href="/user/show/1758594-patrick-gibson">Patrick Gibson</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1758594-patrick-gibson?shelf=contemporary-literature">contemporary-literature</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer39813874" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6498774486184750476">I am from the ‘sturm und drang’ school of life. I can only read a Hesse novel with Mahler playing in the background. The more angst, the better. Give me irrational anguish, sorrow, torment. <br/>In college, I carried Hesse novels under my arm the way super-Christians carry their Bibles like five day pads. Agony and gloom where never far. And I was of the opinion Hans Giebenrath was my autobiography. Contemporaries were raging against the system screamed copies of ‘Catcher in the Rye,’ while I opted f</span>
  <span id="freeText6498774486184750476" style="display:none">I am from the ‘sturm und drang’ school of life. I can only read a Hesse novel with Mahler playing in the background. The more angst, the better. Give me irrational anguish, sorrow, torment. <br />In college, I carried Hesse novels under my arm the way super-Christians carry their Bibles like five day pads. Agony and gloom where never far. And I was of the opinion Hans Giebenrath was my autobiography. Contemporaries were raging against the system screamed copies of ‘Catcher in the Rye,’ while I opted for a pseudo-European, post-Wagner leitmotif singing the ballad of ‘Beneath the Wheel.’ <br />Of course, I wasn’t really a brilliant child ground and crushed by adults fostering an educational system designed to pound the spirit and vanquish imagination. Hans, the protagonist in this novel, faced no greater challenge to his soul than any student today. It was (and is) the beauty of the prose that shattered my world. A product of comic books and forced curriculum, this post-romantic epistle was one of the first novels to grab me by the spleen and twist.<br /><br />I am re-reading the Hesse novels now as (sort of) an adult. I wonder if I will see what I saw then. I know ‘Beneath the Wheel’ is Hesse’s first published book and a primer for the increasing complexity of the later works. The struggle with the dark side personified by close friendships is better expressed in ‘Narcissus and Goldman,’ but for a treatise on themes of antiestablishment, personal freedom and the struggle all men face in their path through life to be themselves in the face of society pressures, this is an excellent primer. To conform rather than being true to oneself is the basis for many of Hesse’s books. The fact that the Nazi’s picked his books to burn is a good signal to ‘read’ and ‘keep reading.’<br /><br />“At this very instant the boy who was the object of all these threats was drifting slowly down the cool river. All nausea, shame and suffering had passed from him; the cold bluish autumn night looked down on the dark shape of his drifting body and the dark water played with his hands and hair and bloodless lips. No one saw him floating downstream, except perhaps an otter setting out even before daybreak for the hunt, eying him cagily as he glided past without a sound. No one knew how he came to be in the water. Perhaps the sight of the beautiful water had attracted him and when he bent over the water the night and the pale moon had seemed so peaceful and restful that weariness and fear drove him with quiet inevitability into the shadow of death.”<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="6498774486184750476" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


