  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1931488202" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1931488202" />
    <a title="Kelsey Dangelo-Worth" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16513891-kelsey-dangelo-worth"><img alt="Kelsey Dangelo-Worth" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1358384336p2/16513891.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1931488202?book_show_action=true">Mar 08, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kelsey Dangelo-Worth" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kelsey Dangelo-Worth" href="/user/show/16513891-kelsey-dangelo-worth">Kelsey Dangelo-Worth</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1931488202" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18250150494065567711">Teachers are cruel assholes that only seek to destroy the individuality, art, and childhood of their students and destroy all the poetry of the books they teach. <br/><br/>It’s No Child Left Behind, the Bildungsroman/Incredibly Tragic Novel. <br/><br/>So, me, an English teacher of little bildungsroman adolescents moving from childhood to adulthood, in the present time where we are all embracing of individuality and art, a nature lover and a lover of small town life, I at once agree with the beauty and message of th</span>
  <span id="freeText18250150494065567711" style="display:none">Teachers are cruel assholes that only seek to destroy the individuality, art, and childhood of their students and destroy all the poetry of the books they teach. <br /><br />It’s No Child Left Behind, the Bildungsroman/Incredibly Tragic Novel. <br /><br />So, me, an English teacher of little bildungsroman adolescents moving from childhood to adulthood, in the present time where we are all embracing of individuality and art, a nature lover and a lover of small town life, I at once agree with the beauty and message of this book and also felt like I was being hit over the head with it repeatedly while struggling through the melodramatic slog.<br /><br />This book and I got off on the wrong foot right away with its “these country people are all Philistines” tone, and when Hans (the tortured boy genius who works his youth away to be the best at school and who is overworked by his teachers), burnt out and sickly and dying, flunks out of school and falls in love with and over idealizes the common people. I’m not sure which one is worse. Everything in the book is black and white, perfect and evil. It's dreamlike and fairytale like, but the narrative voice and the slog through it all is tedious and overblown.<br /><br />I like the message: let kids be kids. Let kids enjoy childhood, let them play and grow and enjoy life and find out who they are. Don’t be a snob, don’t destroy poetry for what it is (the art of capturing the soul and the world—shown beautifully in the poetry of this book). Great message, though, maybe it was preaching to the choir? Maybe the characters felt too delicate and unreal? Maybe there wasn't enough poetry? Maybe it was too predictable? Too melodramatic? Something just didn't work for me.<br /><br />The book is beautifully written, has a true eye for people and character and description, for sentiment. But, when I finished, I just didn’t feel like I was left with anything. No complexity, nothing to ponder or wonder or challenge my thinking, no character (except perhaps the rebellious, angry poet kid) or scene or anything that stayed with me. It seemed trite. <br /><br />I was warned not to judge Hesse based on this book. He’s considered a genius. I’m not quite seeing it here. I was left with: meh, ok. Grade: B- <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="18250150494065567711" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review1931488202">
  <td colspan="2">
