  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2951866555" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2951866555" />
    <a title="Josh" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5258058-josh"><img alt="Josh" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1490047542p2/5258058.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2951866555?book_show_action=true">Nov 16, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Josh" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Josh" href="/user/show/5258058-josh">Josh</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/10553815-beneath-the-wheel">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2951866555" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8996369045756106831">For a while, I thought this book would be one of my favorites of the year. Hesse describing the experiences of Hans at school are truly great and cause one to question the educational approaches of some schools. However, the final 1/3 of the book that follows Hans post-school adventures drags. Perhaps Hesse was going for a deeper meaning with his death by drowning, but given that it happens in the final pages long after he has left school, it feels jarring and out of place more than had he taken</span>
  <span id="freeText8996369045756106831" style="display:none">For a while, I thought this book would be one of my favorites of the year. Hesse describing the experiences of Hans at school are truly great and cause one to question the educational approaches of some schools. However, the final 1/3 of the book that follows Hans post-school adventures drags. Perhaps Hesse was going for a deeper meaning with his death by drowning, but given that it happens in the final pages long after he has left school, it feels jarring and out of place more than had he taken his life definitively as he contemplates briefly after leaving school. It was also quite a struggle to feel any kind of empathy for Hans when Emma abruptly disappears and suddenly, despite him being less than warm towards her, is angered that she left without a real goodbye. Of course, it is what one would expect from a teenager, but it feels like something ripped out of a YA novel in an otherwise more adult book. <br /><br />Overall, not a terrible read, but I think Hesse should have either strengthened the final 1/3 or made it a novella. </span>
  <a data-text-id="8996369045756106831" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

